title: No Veteran Left Behind | A Memorial Day Silent Protest
description:
This is a SILENT protest to bring visibility to and honor our Veterans hosted by Indivisible Acworth. We invite our community to stand in solidarity with our veterans.

We are hosting a silent protest on Sunday, May 25th at the Cobb VA North Clinic in Marietta to raise awareness regarding the assault to veterans' benefits, entitlements, and access to care. 

On Thursday, the US Department of Veterans Affairs ended a mortgage rescue program that has helped almost 20,000 veterans avoid foreclosure and keep their homes. Approximately 90,000 VA loans are at risk of foreclosure and this number continues to increase as more and more veterans are illegally terminated from their Federal jobs by DOGE. 

If the administration can cut this program, reduce vital staff, and create restrictions to the Suicide Hotline, what else do they plan to cut? 

We must gather in solidarity behind the veteran community and we must stand up and fight in memory of the veterans who stood up to, and lost their lives in their combat against fascism and human rights violations.

Because Memorial Day is a solemn day of remembrance, we ask that protestors do not scream and that signage remains RESPECTFUL and relates ONLY to cuts to veterans programs, supporting our veterans, supporting VA staff, and signs that honor the fallen and defend the living.

Sign ideas include, but are not limited to: ﻿﻿﻿﻿

﻿"Honor the Fallen. Care for the Living."﻿﻿
"They Fought for Us — Now We Fight for Them."
"Cuts to VA = Dishonor to Their Sacrifice."
"Memorial Day Is More Than Words — Fund the VA!"
﻿"Project 2025: Betraying the Oath to Those Who Took One."
"Protect the VA, Protect the Promise."
"Fully Staff the VA — Lives Depend on It."
"No More Delays. No More Cuts. No More Excuses."
"Veterans Before Politics."
"We Lost Brothers/Sisters in War — Don’t Lose Them to Policy."
"No Vet Should Fight for Benefits They Earned in Combat."﻿﻿
"From Battlefield to Bureaucracy — Stop the War on Veterans."
"Veterans Deserve Dignity, Not Budget Cuts."

Again, please keep signs respectful. There is a time and place for more humorous or abrasive messaging, but we are showing solidarity with our vets.

title: WORKSHOP | Yes, you can host a house party!
description:
**Why host a house party?**  Yes, door knocks, phone banks, postcards, rallies are all important organizing tools.  But in 2025-26, we need to do something more and different to win.  House parties can:

- Reach voters outside of our political bubbles

- Have friend and neighbor conversations with those who support our democratic values

- Inoculate voters against the onslaught of right-wing media

- Expand our volunteer base

**Are you thinking about hosting a house party, but don't know how to get started?**  If you've never hosted one before (and even if you're a fellow introvert), or just want a refresher, join the Bay Area Coalition every Monday, 5 pm (PT) / 7 pm (CT) / 8 pm (ET) for our ** *nationwide* ** house party workshop ...

 - How to plan your house party

 - Tips and tools for hosting conversations with your friends, neighbors, colleagues

*You'll leave the workshop fired up and ready to host your house party!*

Sign up here for ** *California* ** house party workshops - https://www.mobilize.us/cadems/event/759747/

title: March for a Car Free Silver Lake Park

address_lines: Silver Lake Park Road & Forest Avenue

description:
Silver Lake Park was envisioned as the Central Park of Staten Island’s North Shore. Home to dozens of wildlife species, including a family of nesting bald eagles, a weekly fun run, and a well used road for running, biking, playing, roller skating, and track practices, it’s been an oasis of open space since it was closed to vehicle traffic in 2020.  A haphazard move backed by Councilwoman Hanks, District Attorney McMahon, and Borough President Fossella to reintroduce vehicle traffic to the park is putting lives at risk. 

If you agree that parks are no place for cars, join Transportation Alternatives on May 10th for a march on the offices of Councilwoman Hanks and District Attorney McMahon! 

We will meet at the intersection of Silver Lake Park Road and Forest Avenue before a 1.7-mile march downhill to the offices of Councilwoman Hanks and District Attorney McMahon at 130 Stuyvesant Ave.

title: ShutDown GEO Aurora presents one night only Film Screening of 'And Water Brings Tomorrow'
description:
***Información en español a continuación****
Join us for a one night only screening of a new documentary film, And Water Brings Tomorrow.  The screening will be followed by a live Q&A with the filmmaker, Ashley Hunt.

And Water Brings Tomorrow is a film about change that looks at closed prisons around the U.S., considering what they’ve turned into, the community efforts behind their closure, and the forms of loss and reckoning that their closure does and does not address. 

Light Refreshments are included. Registration for a ticket is required. 

Tickets are free, however sliding scale donations are highly encouraged at the door to support our local Shut Down GEO campaign. Suggested donation is $10, $15 or $20. No one will be turned away due to lack of funds.  https://secure.afsc.org/a/shut-down-geo

Hosts:
Shut Down GEO Aurora is a coalition of individuals and organizations seeking to close Immigration and Customs Enforcement's for-profit prison run by GEO Group, Inc. in Aurora, CO. The Coalition is working with the community to vision new uses for the land and building and to fight an upcoming contract renewal. 

The Denver Justice and Peace Committee (DJPC) is a grassroots organization, that promotes human rights, economic, and environmental justice through education and nonviolent activism to support communities, seeking justice for all people. We stand in solidarity with peoples in the Americas, particularly with oppressed communities in Latin America.

The American Friends Service Committee (AFSC) promotes a world free of violence, inequality, and oppression. Guided by the Quaker belief in the divine Light within each person, we nurture the seeds of change and the respect for human life to fundamentally transform our societies and institutions. We work with people and partners worldwide, of all faiths and backgrounds, to meet urgent community needs, challenge injustice, and build peace.
**************************
Acompáñenos a la proyección, de una sola noche de estreno, del nuevo documental "And Water Brings Tomorrow". Tras la proyección, habrá una sesión de preguntas y respuestas en vivo con la cineasta Ashley Hunt.

And Water Brings Tomorrow es una película que examina a los cárceles 
cerradas por la comunidad, considerando en qué se han convertido, los esfuerzos comunitarios tras su cierre y las formas de pérdida y la reflexión que su cierre aborda y no aborda.

Se incluye unas meriendas ligeras. 

Boletos: Las entradas son gratuitas, pero se agradecen las donaciones en la puerta para apoyar nuestra campaña local Shut Down GEO. Se sugiere una donación de $10, $15 o $20. No se rechazará a nadie por falta de fondos. https://secure.afsc.org/a/shut-down-geo


Anfitriones:
"Cierren GEO Aurora" es una coalición de personas y organizaciones que buscan cerrar la prisión con fines de lucro del Servicio de Inmigración y Control de Aduanas (ICE), administrada por GEO Group, Inc en Aurora, CO. La coalición está trabajando con la comunidad para visualizar nuevos usos para el terreno y el edificio, y para luchar contra una próxima renovación de contrato.

El Comité de Justicia y Paz de Denver (DJPC) es una organización de base que promueve los derechos humanos, la justicia económica y ambiental a través de la educación y el activismo no violento para apoyar a las comunidades y buscar la justicia para todas las personas. Nos solidarizamos con los pueblos de las Américas, en particular con las comunidades oprimidas de Latinoamérica.

El Comité de Servicio de los Amigos Americanos (AFSC) promueve un mundo libre de violencia, desigualdad y opresión. Guiados por la creencia cuáquera en la Luz divina que reside en cada persona, cultivamos las semillas del cambio y el respeto por la vida humana para transformar profundamente nuestras sociedades e instituciones. Trabajamos con personas y socios de todo el mundo, de todas las religiones y orígenes, para atender las necesidades urgentes de la comunidad, combatir la injusticia y construir la paz.

What Is The People’s Parade?

The People’s Parade is a nationwide day of action, art, remembrance, and resistance taking place on June 14, 2025. It reclaims patriotism from authoritarianism, rejecting the militarization of civic identity in favor of multiracial solidarity, joy, and collective memory.

Why June 14?
June 14 is Flag Day. It is also Donald Trump’s birthday. In 2025, Trump has planned a military parade to mark the 250th anniversary of the U.S. Army. The People’s Parade offers a defiant and joyful alternative: honoring the people who have always made America, not the weapons that claim to defend it.

title: Lompoc Indivisible Monthly Membership Meeting
description:
Join us for our monthly membership meeting at the Lompoc Public Library's Grossman Gallery.  

SUNDAY MAY 18, 2025 at 3:00 PM

We are a group of people who want to turn fear, anger, and grief into action. We are coming together as a community to hold each other up, protect each other, and fight for our values. To do this we will grit our teeth, look forward, put one foot in front of the other, and work relentlessly to prevail over anti-democratic extremism. 

We come from a variety of backgrounds and lived experiences, but we share so much in common. We believe that immigrants, BIPOC, and LGBTQ+ people deserve to feel safe, have respect, and be cared for in our community. We believe women should have freedom to make their own healthcare decisions. And we acknowledge that America has yet to live up to its true promise – but we shall continue to strive to get us all there, together. **Indivisible. With Liberty and Justice for all.**

description:
Come to our book club discussion of “The Small and the Mighty.”
The author, Sharon McMahon, shows us that America's true greatness comes not from the presidents or aristocrats but from ordinary people doing extraordinary things. 
You'll meet unforgettable characters: a woman riding a white horse down Pennsylvania Ave, a young boy in a Japanese incarceration camp, a formerly enslaved mother on a mission, a poet on a train, and a teacher facing her enemies with courage.
Reading is optional—discussion and community are the goals.
Come be inspired by the real people who built a more just, peaceful, and free America—and discover how small actions still shape our world today.

title: Hold Them Accountable!: Attend the Camden County Commissioners Meetings
description:
**Hold them accountable!**

The Camden County Commissioners control a giant budget of nearly half a billion dollars. Behind closed doors, they regularly shuffle new loyalists into office. The Commissioners have enormous power when it comes to awarding contracts and deciding how our county tax dollars will be allocated.

Their meetings are far from resident-friendly--held as they are in the middle of the workday. But it's essential that Camden County residents keep an eye on this often overlooked level of government. There's little to no reporting on the decision making of our county government and if we don't attend, all we can expect is Norcross machine PR spin. 

So it's up to us. We can bread and circuses or justice. 

**Please join us in working to keep our county government accountable to the people! We deserve officials who are elected, not appointed! The public money's deserve a fair accounting. That can only happen if we show up!**
